The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Nation Briefs
                                                                                                                 NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	 New Delhi, Jan. 4 (PTI): The Supreme Court has upheld the dismissal of a BSF constable who had refused to take food during a weeks rigorous imprisonment.           
	Ramvir Singh had also refused to take part in a pack drill to protest the punishment imposed for taking leave without notice. Singhs appeal in Punjab and Haryana High Court had been dismissed earlier.                   
	 Patna (PTI): Railway minister Lalu Prasad will deliver lectures to Japanese students on the turnaround in the Indian Railways. Lalu Prasad will leave for Japan on January 11 for a 10-day trip on an invitation from the Japan government. He will study the working of the railways there, an official said.                   
	 Bangalore (PTI): Six prominent IT companies in the city, including Infosys and Wipro, received emails threatening to blow up their buildings two days ago, joint commissioner of police B. Gopal Hosur said on Sunday. The companies immediately informed the police.                  
	 New Delhi (PTI): The question paper of an entrance examination that has been already held and its answer key can now be sought under the RTI Act, the Central Information Commission has ruled. The commission reversed its previous directive, which had exempted disclosure of such information citing larger public interest.                  
	 New Delhi (PTI): Five persons were detained at on Sunday at Indira Gandhi International Airport after crackers, gun powder and battery clips were found in their vehicle but were released after verification. Investigations had revealed that the items were used for a film shoot, police said.                   
	 New Delhi (PTI): Former President A.P.J. Abdul Kalam was admitted to Army Research and Referral Hospital on Sunday after he developed skin infection. Doctors said Kalam, 77, was diagnosed with skin infection but refused to give any detail. His condition is stated to be stable.                                                                                                                            
